{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01QZPMYLEcn7BWQKr3b6Dpsp","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Let me analyze each behavior carefully using the KEY-QUESTIONS framework.\n\n**Behavior 1**: The speech-to-text output preserves speaker labels so that the summary can attribute statements to specific attendees.\n\n- MOCK-MISS: This is about whether the speech-to-text API actually returns speaker labels in its response. The failure could be: (a) the API doesn't return labels, (b) the code doesn't parse/preserve them correctly. If we're testing that the code correctly parses speaker labels from API responses, that could be Integration (module boundary between STT API client and transcript parser). But if we're testing that the STT API *actually* returns speaker labels, that's System (real external API call).\n\n\n- REAL-INFRA: The speech-to-text API is a real external service, and the behavior fundamentally depends on whether it actually performs speaker diarization. Mocking it would hide the real failure mode — that the actual STT service might not return speaker labels for the audio we're processing.\n- LLM-DEP: Speaker diarization isn't fully deterministic; the same audio might produce slightly different speaker assignments across runs, so this behavior has inherent variability.\n- AGENTIC-SCOPE: The question is whether we're testing the code's ability to parse and preserve speaker labels from the STT output (Integration), or whether we're testing whether the real STT service actually produces those labels (System/Agentic). The latter requires the real API because mocking would always succeed.\n\nThe core issue is that \"preserves speaker labels\" only fails end-to-end when the real STT API is involved — if we mock the STT response with labels already included, the test passes regardless of whether the actual service provides them. So the minimum level has to be System, since the real failure mode only surfaces with the actual external API call. The core question is whether the STT API actually returns speaker labels in the first place — mocking the API would mask that failure mode. So I need a System-level test that calls the real STT service to verify labels are both returned and preserved through the code's data structures.\n\nFor the second behavior, the LLM's ability to extract action items and map them to attendees is the real dependency here. Mocking the LLM with canned output would always pass, so I need to test against actual LLM output to catch cases where it fails to identify or correctly attribute tasks.\n\nFor the third behavior, it's similar — the LLM needs to correctly identify decisions and place them in the right section of the summary. Mocking would hide failures, so this also requires an agentic test with a real LLM call.\n\nFor the fourth behavior, I'm looking at whether the service handles long audio files by splitting them into segments and merging the results coherently. This involves the audio processing pipeline itself.\n\nThe core question is whether the splitting and merging logic works correctly, which could theoretically be tested with mocked STT and LLM. But the requirement for a \"single coherent summary\" is a quality judgment that really depends on the actual LLM output — a fake LLM would always produce coherent results. So the LLM dependency is real here, and this is a multi-step process across multiple modules.\n\nSince we're dealing with multiple sequential agentic steps (transcribing each segment, then merging them), this qualifies as a Workflow test at minimum. Now looking at the full pipeline behavior — uploading real audio, transcribing it, summarizing, and delivering structured output without manual intervention — that's clearly end-to-end and requires real infrastructure.\n\nLet me categorize what I've identified: Behavior 1 needs a real STT API to verify speaker labels are preserved, Behavior 2 requires an LLM to check action item extraction accuracy per attendee, Behavior 3 needs an LLM to validate decision placement in the summary, Behavior 4 is a Workflow since it chains multiple transcription calls with a merge step, and Behavior 5 is also a Workflow covering the entire pipeline with real components.\n\nGoing back to Behavior 1 — when it says \"preserves speaker labels,\" I need to think about what that actually means in context.\n\nThe STT API returns diarized output with speaker labels, and the system should pass those downstream without dropping them. The failure could stem from either the API not having diarization enabled, or the code stripping the labels. The core behavior is about preservation, which points to System-level concerns around whether the real STT API actually returns those labels in the first place. I'll weight this as System with a smaller probability on Agentic since the labels eventually feed into the LLM summary, but the specific behavior is fundamentally about STT output integrity.\n\nFor the probability distribution across test levels: Unit testing gets minimal weight since speaker label preservation isn't really testable in isolation, Integration gets some weight since I could mock the STT response, but System dominates because the real API configuration and diarization settings are what matter most.\n\nNow I'm assigning probabilities for the remaining behaviors. Action items per attendee is almost entirely Agentic—that's pure LLM extraction quality, so it needs the real model. Key decisions in the decisions section follows the same pattern. For the 60-minute splitting and merging behavior, I'm still working through the probability breakdown.\n\nNow I'm sketching out test descriptions for each behavior—starting with a real audio recording test that verifies the STT API preserves speaker labels through the service's internal representation, and then a transcript test where I feed clearly assigned tasks to the LLM and check that the action items list correctly attributes each task to the right person.\n\nNext I'm adding a test for explicit decision statements in the transcript, making sure they land in the decisions field rather than getting buried in narrative or notes, followed by a long-form test with a 60+ minute file to verify the service segments it properly, calls the LLM once per segment plus a merge, and returns a single coherent JSON without duplicates or gaps.\n\nFinally, the end-to-end test uploads a real meeting recording through the deployed service and confirms the full structured JSON summary comes back with all the required fields intact. I'm also validating that the first two tests align with their plan_consistent requirements—the system test needs a real STT call and the agentic test needs a real LLM call.\n\nNow I'm working through the rejection gates for each test case: the integration approach fails because mocking STT output would hide whether the real API actually does speaker diarization, and the workflow/agentic approaches don't apply since the behavior is really about STT capability, not LLM quality. For the LLM extraction test, mocking the LLM always passes, so I need the real model; workflow is rejected because only one agentic step is involved. The multi-segment test requires multiple real LLM calls in sequence, and the merge operation's coherence depends on those real calls working together.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":3,"cache_creation_input_tokens":9800,"cache_read_input_tokens":3199,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":9800},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"eb38bdca-9cca-4632-a4c7-39b4b82a2bc3","uuid":"1e646ed6-6148-4f36-a6b5-4e3c56f3eacf"}
{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01QZPMYLEcn7BWQKr3b6Dpsp","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_01RQgsTHSyhLcB3Vp29kkPKd","name":"StructuredOutput","input":{"behaviors":[{"behavior_id":1,"description":"The speech-to-text output preserves speaker labels so that the summary can attribute statements to specific attendees.","minimum_level":"System","justification":"MOCK-HIDE: mocking the STT API to return pre-labeled output trivially passes, hiding whether the real API is configured to perform speaker diarization at all. The dominant failure mode is that the real STT service either does not return diarization data, or returns it in a format the code silently drops. An in-process fake cannot reproduce this because it would always supply labels exactly as written. Integration rejected: a module-boundary test with a mocked STT client only verifies that the code preserves labels it is handed—not that it ever receives them from the real service. Agentic/Workflow rejected: the behavior is scoped to the STT output layer, not LLM extraction quality, so non-deterministic LLM behavior is not the relevant failure boundary here.","test_description":"Submit a real multi-speaker audio recording to the STT API via the live service client; assert that the returned transcript object contains speaker-labeled segments (e.g., Speaker_0, Speaker_1 identifiers) and that none of those labels are stripped or collapsed before the transcript is handed to the summarizer.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.04,"Integration":0.16,"System":0.58,"Agentic":0.16,"Workflow":0.06}},{"behavior_id":2,"description":"The structured summary contains at least one action item for every attendee who was assigned a task during the meeting.","minimum_level":"Agentic","justification":"LLM-DEP: correctness depends entirely on whether the real LLM correctly identifies every task assignment in the transcript and maps it to the right attendee. This is extraction and attribution quality—a claim about what the model produces, not about code logic. MOCK-HIDE: a mocked LLM returning a canned summary always passes regardless of transcript content, hiding any failure in model comprehension or prompt design. Integration rejected: wiring the summarizer module to a fake LLM proves only that the code routes output correctly, not that the model finds all task assignments. Workflow rejected: only one agentic step (summarization) is the failure boundary; no multi-step sequencing is required.","test_description":"Feed a controlled, real transcript containing clearly assigned tasks for N distinct named attendees (e.g., 'Alice, please draft the contract by Friday; Bob, schedule the follow-up') to the real LLM summarizer and assert that the action_items list in the returned summary contains exactly N entries, each attributed to the correct attendee name.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.02,"Integration":0.05,"System":0.05,"Agentic":0.78,"Workflow":0.1}},{"behavior_id":3,"description":"Key decisions mentioned in the transcript appear in the 'decisions' section of the summary, not buried in the narrative.","minimum_level":"Agentic","justification":"LLM-DEP: the failure mode is that the model either does not recognize a statement as a decision or routes it to a narrative field instead of the decisions field. This is a classification quality claim that only a real LLM call can validate. MOCK-HIDE: a mocked LLM with a hardcoded response always places content in the right field, hiding any model misclassification. Integration rejected: in-process module wiring tests verify that the code reads from summary.decisions correctly, not that the real model populates it correctly. Workflow rejected: a single summarization call is the relevant failure boundary; multi-step sequencing is not required to surface this defect.","test_description":"Send a real transcript containing N explicit decision statements (e.g., 'We agreed to proceed with vendor X', 'The team decided to postpone the launch') to the live LLM summarizer and assert that each statement—or its semantic equivalent—appears in the decisions field of the structured output and is absent from any narrative or notes fields.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.02,"Integration":0.04,"System":0.05,"Agentic":0.79,"Workflow":0.1}},{"behavior_id":4,"description":"When the audio file is longer than 60 minutes, the service splits it into segments and processes them sequentially, merging the results into a single coherent summary.","minimum_level":"Workflow","justification":"MULTI-STEP: this behavior requires multiple real agentic steps in sequence—at minimum one STT call per audio segment plus a final LLM merge call. The claimed outcome ('single coherent summary') is a quality assertion about the merge step's output, which only a real LLM can satisfy non-trivially. Integration rejected: mocking STT and LLM verifies split-and-stitch code logic but cannot confirm that the merged summary is coherent or that the real STT+LLM chain produces compatible outputs across segment boundaries. Agentic rejected: a single-step agentic test does not exercise the sequential segment processing and merge path, which is where the structural failure (duplicate sections, broken attribution chains, incoherent narrative across boundary) would manifest. System rejected: the failure boundary is the multi-step AI pipeline, not OS/network primitives.","test_description":"Submit a real audio file exceeding 60 minutes to the service; assert that the service internally produces at least 2 STT segment transcripts, invokes the LLM at least twice (once per segment or once for each segment plus one merge), and returns a single JSON summary document that contains no duplicate section keys, no empty sections, and at least one coherent action item or decision sourced from content in the second segment.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.02,"Integration":0.05,"System":0.06,"Agentic":0.17,"Workflow":0.7}},{"behavior_id":5,"description":"The full pipeline — upload audio, transcribe, summarize, deliver structured output — completes without manual intervention for a real meeting recording.","minimum_level":"Workflow","justification":"REAL-INFRA + MULTI-STEP: this behavior explicitly names every stage of the pipeline (upload, transcribe, summarize, deliver) with a real recording, requiring real HTTP upload, a real STT API call, a real LLM call, and a real structured-output delivery. Any of these stages can fail independently, and the claim 'without manual intervention' means all must succeed in sequence. Integration rejected: in-process module wiring with mocked I/O cannot expose real API authentication failures, network timeouts, payload-size limits, or model refusals on real audio content. System rejected: the pipeline includes a real LLM summarization step whose output correctness depends on model behavior, elevating the requirement beyond System. Agentic rejected: the multi-step sequential nature (transcribe → summarize → deliver) satisfies the Workflow criterion directly.","test_description":"Upload a real, representative meeting recording (5–10 minutes) to the service's upload endpoint using a real HTTP client; poll or await the pipeline completion callback; assert that the final HTTP response contains a valid structured JSON summary with non-empty action_items, decisions, and attendee_attributions fields, and that no human confirmation step was required at any stage.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.01,"Integration":0.02,"System":0.06,"Agentic":0.08,"Workflow":0.83}}]},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":3,"cache_creation_input_tokens":9800,"cache_read_input_tokens":3199,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":9800},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"eb38bdca-9cca-4632-a4c7-39b4b82a2bc3","uuid":"235bd07b-6fde-4ea7-8fb2-d49a6ea1858d"}
